    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-13T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-13T17:00:00-05:00" n="39"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d39">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 103.96/254</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-13T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 13, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6571. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName> [from
                    War Trade Board]:</p>
                <p>No. 99. Your No. 109. British Embassy has been taking up with us direct matter of
                    eliminating call at Halifax; also, Captain <persName>Mackin</persName> of
                    British Admiralty, in charge at Halifax, has been here in conference with our
                    naval representatives. Agreement has been reached satisfactory to British
                    Embassy and Captain <persName>Mackin</persName>, which provides for elimination
                    of call at Halifax by vessels proceeding from United States ports and search at
                    United States ports by United States officials assisted and advised by British
                    Admiralty officers who will be brought here from Halifax.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d39fn1">Telegram to the Ambassador in Great Britain, June 14, No.
                        8270, for <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName>,
                        No. 679, states: “Present arrangement with the British Government … provides
                        for a search in United States ports of only those vessels which load their
                        [entire] cargoes in the United States.” (File No. 656.119/484.)</note>
                    British Embassy and Captain <persName>Mackin</persName> have cabled Foreign
                    Office and Admiralty respectively asking their approval of foregoing
                    arrangements. Upon securing such approval we understand call at Halifax will at
                    once be eliminated.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
